i think when you start focusing on stuff that you like drawing, rather than what you should draw because it looks nicer, is when you get a lot of freedom and are able to make stuff youre not unsatisfied it

this is just from memory
the basis is that you boil a bunch of potatoes in some kind of stock + water mixture and also soften(or caramellize) onions on the side. The length of the recipe p much just depends on how long you let the onions cook. aftwr all thats done you put onions into the  pot with the potatoes, add like a flour slurry in there(1 tsp of flour i think??) and then mix it all together with  a immersive blender(oorr you can let it cool and put it in a reguler blender)

Serve with some croutons, roaster seeds and/or some herbs and you have a lovely soup :)
a while back i found this rlly comforting golden potato soup recipe, its really easy but just takes a long time to get done

there is definitely discussion to be had about how to categorise sports in order for it to be fair, but this doesnt line up with your claim that ‚Äúpeople use sexuality/gender for advantage‚Äù

No trans woman in sport becomes trans just to have an advantage over other women. Theyre just trans women who happen to do competitive sport. This can actually often put them at a disadvantage: they will become the focus of discourse, people will start talking about their body(which can be really dehumanising if you think about it ‚Äî imagine the whole world discussing whether your win was fair or not because of your genitalia. Yes, there are other biological factors, but anti trans people reaaaallly love talking about the genitals..)

Ive heard of trans women who had a happy life doing sport just because thats what she loved, at no advantage over others, but then that is all torn away once she got outed. Imagine not only losing your friends but also becoming hated by the internet. Imagine everyone talking about your body, uninvited.

the cons visibly outweigh the trivial pros. Saying people are using gender for an advantage dismisses all the suffering and backlash they have to endure

anyone else got that Someone that whenever you remember their existence, you just feel much calmer n satisfied and happy... i dont know how to dsecribe it but it feels like the color lilac filling my body. its not hot like love and passion nor is it energetic and full of adrenaline. but its not frigid and sharp either. its just something soft and cooling. like a sea breeze? yeah

i hvent spoken to her in like 2 months and before that we hadnt... spoken for 2 years. cuz i messed up <:TeriSweat:973794147683151912> so thinking about her used to mkae me super anxious and mad. 

but before then we were really close friends. perhaps too close. it ended up toxic which is why we cut it off for so long as well. i was aware *something* was wrong so i was trying desperately to fix it.. which was the downfall. because i was to desperate to be next to her at all times, i refused to accept distance was the solution, until i exploded. 

I ended up being quite manipulative for some time after that, trying to maintain my importance among friendgroups so they wouldn't cast me aside for the awful things i'd done. I succeeded, of course, but it was very unsatisfying. I was in fear of my secret of being evil exposed. So I did the scary leap of faith and just started being unapologetically myself. Rather just crumble the wall myself than let others do it.

That allowed me to develop genuine, deep relationships with others, although forcefully at times. I became more independent since I no longer depended on her to tell me what's good, bad, etc. its not like she abused me, definitely not. I just saw her as that important. I remember occasionally asking her if i was really a good person and she'd always reply with yes cuz i was her best friend as well

anyways, back in may she sent me a friendrequest. we talked things through. now my feelings towards her arent intense in either direction and it's all just very sweet. I still feel a strong connection towards, as if we were fated to meet

also, theres these things called counter-types which means the combination of the core type and the instinct creates something that seems to act against the very foundation of the type. but do not be fooled, they very much still have the same fixation/passion/sin.
you *may* find when reading the 27 subtype descriptions that within some types, all the subtypes appear social or for others, all appear self-preservation like. but keep in mind that some types will inherently be more defensive of their wellbeing, or more social and extraverted, or more withdrawn and introspective.
so about instincts! There is 3 instincts: self-preservation(sp), sexual(sx) and social(so). If you combine these with the 9 enneagrams, you get a total of 27 different types. The names are quite self explanatory already, although sx needs some clarification, so lets get to the descriptions.

Self-preservation: As the name implies, if a person has this instinct, theyre instinctually going to focus on their own safety and material wellbeing first. They may be hyper-vigilant, sort of like keeping track of their health, hunger and thirst bars. Theyre focused in on spending their own resources as little as possible.

Sexual: The people of this type do not necessarily have to be sexual, although it is common to be so. This type is defined by the intensity and chemistry it strives towards. They may seek out thrilling rides, exciting stories, or fun partners to spend their time with. They don't fully focus in on themselves, but rather the relationship/chemistry they have with another person. 

Social: A person of this instinct will naturally be drawn towards social activities and what's going on with the world. They care about the relationships they have with others and the collective health of the group.  While the SP is the most earthly and concerned with material goods and the SX is most concerned with the intensity of emotion and energy, SO is most concerned with the intellectual.

You may find some similarities when comparing the triads and the instincts. You could correlate SX to the emotional heart triad, SO to the rational mind triad and SP to the very body-focused gut triad. But this doesnt mean that if youre a person of x triad you must also be y instinct. You can be any of the 9 enneagram types while also being any of the 3 enneagram instincts.

thats it for todays enneagram lesson
so what are the deadly sins of each type? here we go

1 - wrath
2 - pride
3 - vanity
4 - envy
5 - avarice/greed
6 - cowardice
7 - gluttony
8 - lust
9 - sloth
What does core, externalised and internalised mean in this case?

Core means that its in the middle. they are the most focused on avoiding the feeling specific to that triad. This means e9s are the least aware of anger, they are ignorant of themselves. E6s are cautious and fearful, trying to protect themselves against any danger. They try to make their surroundings as safe as possible. E3s avoid feeling shameful by being succesful and good in the eye of others. They must be efficient.

Externalised means that the feeling respective to their triads comes from the outside. E8s are reactive and act in the means of justice. Their anger is shortlived, since they lack any real anger inside. E5s are avoidant of the world because the world itself causes fear. In order to avoid fear, they must retreat to the safe space of their own home or head. E2s lack inner shame, they are prideful and advertise themselves as great to avoid being shamed by others.


Internalised means that the feeling respective to their triads comes from the Inside. E1s are the most critical because theyre always feeling anger. Its bubbling underneath their surface. They wont stop being angry until everything is ideal. E7s are the most active and fun because they cannot let their mind rest on the negative, the fear is coming from the inside so they do external activities to avoid feeling afraid. E4s are the most shameful, they feel an inner lack compared to others. They always feel like grass is greener on the other side.
enneagram itself has spiritual origins, being based on the 7 deadly sins. cant remember who invented the enneagram but he was a funky dude and thought the enneagram symbol was literally the guide of the universe or sth weird like that. 
The version of enneagram I focus on is based on the teachings of Oscar Ichazo and Claudio Naranjo, although i know a bit more about naranjo than ichazo.
The version of enneagram you will find the most online is Riso and Huddsons enneagram, which is a very simplified system of the enneagram and ignored the deadly sins. These do not have as much depth and are often considered mischaracterisations of the original types.

With that out of the way, lets get into the actual introduction to the system.
The enneagram wheel(which consists of 9 points) can be divided into three aspects of the human body: body, mind and soul.
Everyone experiences all three triads and all nine enneagrams, but will usually stay mostly in one type. 
Body is the most instinctual, the most reactive to physical threats. The three types found in this triad are characterised by anger. At the centre is e9, which is also at the top of the circle. e9 is the core of anger, e8 is the externalised version of it and e1 is the internalised version of it.
Mind is the most intellectual, the most rational, the most proactive. The three tpyes found in this triad are characterised by fear. e6 is the core of fear, e5 is the externalised version of it and e7 is the internalised version of it.
Soul is the most emotional, the most dependant on social connections. The three types found in this triad are characterised by shame. e3 is the core of shame, e2 is the externalised version of it and e4 is the internalised version of it.

(Continued) then compensatory is seeing a worse version of yourself in your reflection, hiding it from everyone and then replacing the mirror with a drawing of yourself where youre all great and mighty
guys i love my mental health course and the class today was so fun so im gonna infodump

ok so basically a big part of healthy self esteem is EGO. Contrary to the everyday use of the word, ego/egoism in psychological terms is an important quality to have, which prioritises your own needs before others. This is important because if you dont prioritise yourself first, your health(mental, physical and social) will also decline and may end up hurting/confusing others in the process. We cannot truly take care of others until we take care of ourselves. Think of it as the oxugen masks during an emergency in the plane!

soo what is self esteem? Self esteem is how you value you, your actions and accomplishments. There are 5 different kinds:
- healthy
- lowered
- heightened
- compensatory
- variable (bouncing back and forth on lowered and heightened self esteem)

Lowered self esteem may be characterised by feelings of self-blame, undervaluing your own positive qualities, abandoning your own needs, fleeing or attacking others in conflict, etc.

Heightened self esteem can be characterised by the exact opposite: blaming others for everything, undervaluing your own negative qualities or the positive qualities of others, putting yourself first and expecting others to prioritise you as well, however they may ALSO flee or attack others in conflict and may ahve the exact negative emotions as people with low self esteem. Despite beingn high, it is not healthy.

Healthy self esteem is about balance. It is prioritising yourself above others(ego) but not expecting kthers to do the same. It doesnt over/undervalue any of their qualities and can feel at peace. They deal with conflict respectfully and reasonably.


Compensatory can be described as low self esteem which tries to act like the greatest. If low self esteem is like looking into the mirror and seeing a worse reflection of yourself and high self esteem is looking into the mirror and seeing a greater, omnipotent version of yourself,

what sp/so 163 means btw:
sp/so - instinctual stacking, the one you have rn shows that your instincts are self preservation > social > sexual(not literally sexual but thats the name)
163 - trifix.. the first number (1) is your core aka main tpye, the other two are from the mind and heart triad respectively. theres three triads (mind, gut, heart) and your trifix consists of one type from each triad

Please fill out all the questions with as much detail as possible! One sentence results will not lead to accurate typings. Btw more questions might be needed to figure out your type, especially if you want your subtypes and tritype.
*Recommended to do this on google docs*

1. What is your relationship with anger? (from yourself or others!) How do you experience and respond to it?

2. What is your relationship with fear? How do you experience and respond to it?

3. How do you respond to/cope with negative events or feelings?

4. When do you feel the happiest? Describe what feeling (example: calm, worthy, loved, etc.) and what events cause that for you!

5. What does vulnerability mean to you? When do you experience it? (don‚Äôt feel obligated to go into too much detail as this is a more personal question)

6. How good are you when it comes to addressing your own needs? How good are you at addressing the needs of others?

7. What kind of people/traits do you dislike?

8. Do you feel comfortable with confrontation? Why or why not?

9. What is your relationship with self-sufficiency? Is it important to you? How do you seek it?

10. How do you wish to be perceived? What do you do to appear this way? To what lengths do you go?

11. What is your relationship to authority?

12. What about your identity is unique from others?

13. How do you avoid criticism and rejection? Are these things you feel strongly about avoiding?

14. What brings you the most shame or guilt in your life? What is your relationship to shame?

oh actually tests can be really misleading and dont show the full picture
1] The complete enneagram (Beatrice Chestnut) - read the passions, introductions, differences between triads and instinctual variants, some of the trait structure too is fine but it's better in other books so id suggest only focusing on passions from her book.. subtypes from Beatrice aren't the best .. it's overall a simplified book for beginners 
2] The enneagram of society (Claudio Naranjo) - also runs you through the passions and give you an understanding of it 
3] The enneagram of passion and virtues (Sandra Maitiri) 
4] Character & Neurosis (Claudio Naranjo) 
leaving it last because it's most complicated and heavy in words but you'll get a grasp over it once you've read the others
5] you can then move on to reading and figuring out your subtypes : 
‚ï∞‚ñ∫ 
all the books are found here:
‚ï∞‚ñ∫ 

‚òÜ extra books to read that are also useful: 
- The spiritual dimensions of the enneagram (Sandra)
- 27 Personalities in search of being (Naranjo)
